| Long Block Data Standard Finalized                                 |
|   from the 30-years-later dept.                                    |
|   posted by kdawson on Tuesday May 01, @17:23 (Data Storage)       |
|   http://hardware.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/01/2021244     |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

An anonymous reader writes "[0]IDEMA has finally [1]released the LBD
(Long Block Data) standard. This standard, in work since 2000, increases
the length of the data blocks of each sector from 512 bytes to 4,096
bytes. This is an update that has been requested for some time by the
hard-drive industry and the development of new drives will start
immediately. The new standard offers many advantages — improved
reliability and higher transfer rates are the two most obvious. While
some manufacturers say the reliability may increase as much as tenfold,
the degree of performance improvement to be expected is a bit more
elusive. Overall improvements include shorter time to format and more
efficient data transfers due to smaller overhead per block during read
and write operations."

Discuss this story at:
    http://hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/01/2021244

Links:
    0. http://www.idema.org/
    1. http://www.sys-con.com/read/368465_p.htm


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Music Decoded From 600-Year-Old Carvings                           |
|   from the rosslyn-motet dept.                                     |
|   posted by kdawson on Tuesday May 01, @17:55 (Music)              |
|   http://science.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/01/2047212      |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

RulerOf writes "Musicians recently [0]unlocked a 600 year old mystery
that had been encoded into the walls of the Rosslyn Chapel in Scotland,
the one featured in The Da Vinci Code. The song was carved into the walls
of the chapel in the form of geometric shapes that a father-son team —
both are musicians and the father is an ex-Royal Air Force code breaker —
finally matched to so-called Chladni patterns (see the [1]Wikipedia
article on cymatics). The recovered melody was paired with traditional
lyrics (translated into Latin) and recorded; the result can be [2]heard
in this video (also linked from [3]the musicians' website). The video
also gives a visual representation of how the engravings match up to the
cymatic patterns." From the Reuters article: "'The music has been frozen
in time by symbolism... [The carvings] are of such exquisite detail and
so beautiful that we thought there must be a message here.' The two men
matched each of the patterns on the carved cubes to a Chladni pitch, and
were able finally to unlock the melody."

Discuss this story at:
    http://science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/01/2047212

Links:
    0. http://www.reuters.com/article/topNews/idUSL014372920070501
    1. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cymatics
    2. http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cy2Dg-ncWoY
    3. http://www.tjmitchell.com/stuart/rosslyn.html


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Death Knell For DDoS Extortion?                                    |
|   from the greener-pastures dept.                                  |
|   posted by kdawson on Tuesday May 01, @19:17 (Security)           |
|   http://it.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/01/2135212           |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]Ron writes "Symantec security researcher Yazan Gable has put forward
an explanation as to [1]why the number of denial of service attacks has
been declining (coincident with the rise of spam). His theory is that DoS
attacks are no longer profitable to attackers. While spam and phishing
attacks directly generate profit, he argues that extortion techniques
often used with DoS attacks are far more risky and often make an attacker
no profit at all. Gable writes: 'So what happens if the target of the
attack refuses to pay? The DoS extortionist is obligated to carry out a
prolonged DoS attack against them to follow through on their threats. For
a DoS extortionist, this is the worst scenario because they have to risk
their bot network for nothing at all. Since the target has refused to
pay, it is likely that they will never pay. As a consequence, the
attacker has to spend time and resources on a lost cause.'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/01/2135212

Links:
    0. mailto:ron@skullsecurity.com
    1. http://www.symantec.com/enterprise/security_response/weblog/2007/04/dos_extortion_is_no_longer_pro.html



